summary:
Behind the Scenes of The Doctors Daughter - Part 6  

Excerpt from the Podcast Commentary from The Doctor’s Daughter, featuring...
caption:
Behind the Scenes of The Doctors Daughter - Part 6

Excerpt from the Podcast Commentary from The Doctor’s Daughter, featuring David Tennant, showrunner Russell T. Davies, and director Alice Troughton

RTD: Actually, Georgia had auditioned for Rose
DT: No! Did she?
RTD: Yeah, yeah, yeah!  Didn’t you know that?  Yes!  Way back at the very beginning, and she was wonderful. It was literally one of those auditions where you thought, “she’s excellent, and…”
DT: She can only have been 14 years old then!?!
RTD: Well I know. Literally we thought, “give her a couple of years and she’ll be fantastic”
DT: Right
RTD: Little knowing that only 3 years have passed and she’s reached all her potential, actually.
DT: Yeah, yeah, yeah.
RTD: She’s very rapidly become very brilliant. Well, she was brilliant to begin with
DT: She’s terrific in this. She went straight on to be one of the leads in… I’m going to forget the name of it…
AT: Spooks Code 9
DT: Spooks Code 9, which is starting soon. I got a message from her yesterday saying that they’d just done a press day…
RTD: Oh God, already?
DT: …and all that she got asked about was this
[ all laugh ]
RTD: Welcome to the rest of your life
DT: Which I don’t think bothered her at all but I’m sure Spooks-Point-Nine-Point-Six were a bit annoyed
[ all laugh again ]

summary: Fortunately, there won’t be any battling between angels and demons, or the Hell and its majestically horrifying structure, in...
body: Fortunately, there won’t be any battling between angels and demons, or the Hell and its majestically horrifying structure, in this “Divine Comedy.” Instead, we will see in here a low-ranking angel, who used to guard the Eastern Gate of Eden, and a “slithering” demon, who’s once called “Crawly” for obvious reasons, working side by side and defying the “effable” plans of their respective “families” to assist an incredibly humanized offspring of the Devil on the account of humans. I honestly can’t wait ‘til the TV adaptation of Good Omens coming out. I’m looking forward to the TVnization of the scene where Aziraphale and Crowley (almost) spread their wings in the face of the Devil! (Image via Douglas Mackinnon)

summary: There was actually a line cut from “The Christmas Invasion” that explained the estuary accent, where it’s shown that part of...
body:
There was actually a line cut from “The Christmas Invasion” that explained the estuary accent, where it’s shown that part of Rose’s personality has infected the new Doctor’s character.

“It’s a shame they cut that!” He exclaims, sounding genuinely peeved. “That was the other reasoning behind it as well, this idea that Rose had imprinted on him and I think it made a nice sense, and it feeds into that whole close relationship that they’ve got and how that was unfolding.”

The Perfect Ten - interview with David Tennant, SFX 143, May 2006
